    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters April 30 with a roster built to exploit stolen base opportunities against high-delivery-time pitchers. **Corbin Carroll** (59.88) leads the charge as our strongest play, buoyed by a substantial +10% combined boost from his spot in the #3 hole and the high probability of success against Woodruff\u2019s deliberate pace. While the matchup against an elite 2.90 xERA arm typically tempers expectations, **Corbin Carroll** remains a mandatory start due to the sheer volume of SB potential. **James Wood** (56.99) follows closely, benefiting from a massive +10% efficiency bump for batting leadoff against Peralta, despite the drag caused by facing a sub-4.00 xERA arm and a formidable catcher pop time.\n\n**Kyle Karros** (56.96) emerges as a sleeper pick, riding a +7% platoon advantage and favorable wind conditions to overcome a lower base projection. Conversely, **Austin Riley** (52.14) faces a tougher path against Valdez; while his efficiency remains solid due to the SB-friendly slow delivery of the opposing starter, he is hamstrung by the SP\u2019s 3.66 xERA and a standard #5 spot in the order. **Brice Turang** (57.03) rounds out the starting group, providing a steady floor that relies heavily on his #2 lineup positioning to compensate for a middling matchup against Soroka. \n\nDepth remains a concern today, as our bench is largely compromised by league-wide scheduling gaps. **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Josh Naylor**, **Tyler Soderstrom**, and **Vinnie Pasquantino** are all inactive, leaving us no viable alternatives to swap into the starting five. We are effectively locked into this configuration, assuming no late-breaking lineup changes for depth pieces like **Jose Caballero**, **Mickey Moniak**, or **Giancarlo Stanton**. Monitor the status of **Seiya Suzuki**, **Trevor Story**, and **Gabriel Moreno** closely; should any of our starters be scratched, we lack the bench depth to maintain our efficiency targets without dipping into reserves like **Max Muncy**, **Luis Campusano**, **Dalton Rushing**, **Zach McKinstry**, **Alex Freeland**, **Carson Williams**, or **Travis Bazzana**. No weather systems currently threaten the card, but the reliance on SB-centric scoring makes the presence of elite defensive catchers like those facing **James Wood** a lingering risk for our stolen base production.",
